ok. so let’s move on to the latin portion of my misidentification shall we ? 

growing up in LA everyone assumed i was latina. to this day if i walk into a latin restaurant people assume i’m going to order in spanish. i should have learned how to speak spanish. sigh. i moved from LA to santa barabara in high school and the latin kids there wouldn’t be my friend because i didn’t speak spanish. this always made me sad.

one of the things i love about walter’s gallery space is this small long gallery which i’ve used a couple times now for installations or interesting groupings of work. 

do you remember making paper chains ? i made a few as an elementary school kid. one time we were supposed to write wishes on the inside. there’s something nostalgic and wonderfully simple about these. and i love the idea of thinking about all of us linked together. 

as per usual i love using alternate materials to what’s expected and i love the whole 2D/3D thing. and of course the shadows 

huge shout out to my MOM who helped me make these links. she crocheted in the car, at home, wherever !! she made two long chains. i made one kong one and one short one 😉 thanks mom. so much. 

also a version of this will be on view @vogueknitlive in february - the 2nd weekend

i mean i do love documenting the “normal”. metro cards certainly fall into that.

i guess i needed a week off of social media 😉

i’m about to start two new rope installations and so my head has been in the planning and thinking stages. nothing glamorous. just math and drawings and concept research. and ordering. and checking the bank account to make sure i’ve got the funds 

i need to clean my studio so badly but i’m fighting that. it’s been cold and there’s a lot of boxes around it and it seems overwhelming. i know i will get to it. not gonna beat myself up about it. thinking that if i stop feeling guilty about it it will seem like less of a mountain. 

this morning i just wanted to play with some concentric like shape. and the idea of connecting them (this loosely relates to the installations. although they are going to be monochromatic ombre) 

so here’s my #colormeditation for a sunday. in #gouache because that’s what my #colortheory students are using so it feels appropriate

today’s #colormeditation 🔺🔺🔺

inspired by quilts and interlocking shapes. testing out how much info you need to see a pattern. what happens when you break that up. how to balance negative space…  also just seeing something and going for it. i saw a t-shirt on tv under a jacket that had some triangles point to point and i thought hmmmm 🤔

and so begins another knot installation. 

someday i want to do one that ombres into the natural cotton ….this one is going to be different though. kind of excited by that !

the metaphor of a slowly deflating balloon 🎈 is kind of undeniable. especially when it says get well soon. 

daylight savings on the heels of some stressful news makes for a tiring sunday morning. but at least i’m not in a flood zone. 

i love how drawing is so immediate. and of course the ribbon had to be thread. was thinking about how i’ve been intermingling textiles and painting and drawing for 20+ years now. and i never tire of it.

when i start thinking about a new piece or new concept i have to iterate it many many times. 

it’s like it has to seep into the fiber of my being so i can begin the slow process of understanding why it’s scratching inside my brain. why it’s a thing. why i like it. what it means. 

i’ve been toying with these amime fishing net patterns for a bit (kind of started when i was in japan and i kept seeing it everywhere and then was given a bag in a store with it). if you’ve been glimpsing it in my stories i’ve been collecting dishes and bowls and towels with the pattern on it 

and i’ve been painting it too. 

gearing up to do something large with it. which means i really have to feel like i understand not only what it does formally but what it means to me to make it. 

#watercolor #sketchbook #indigo #lssketchbook2023

black tourmaline is thought to protect you from negative energy. 

it’s just a beautiful stone. 

and @mel_prest_k alerted me to the fact that @danielsmithartistsmaterials makes a black tourmaline #watercolor. she also gifted me a tube because she rolls like that. 

i’ve been thinking about how i want to use it. thinking about how sometimes we just have to say out loud what we want and need more of in our lives. how often life throws us challenges. both huge and small and how all of that can be draining. tiring. life lessons come in all forms at all times. there’s no pause. 

i’ve been thinking about how tired we all seem to be. how it’s sometimes hard to find a way to rejuvenate. how making things usually makes me feel better. more whole. 

then i started thinking about how humans are always looking for luck. for protection. all cultures. all peoples. for as long as we’ve walked the earth. 

so i’m starting a very small side sketchbook project. a book of luck. small tokens and talismans painted w. the tourmaline.

packing up and organizing for an upcoming exhibition - rediscovering this oldie but goodie

this is the atomic structure of formaldehyde 
yes. the chemical used for preservation of science samples but also used in a lot of manufacturing (like paper) and in cosmetics and medicines as a preservative. 

it’s highly toxic folx. 

these are doilies i crocheted and put over glass balls
3”x8”x8”

i have always loved the atomic structures you see in classrooms and illustrated in textbooks. and i’m toying here with the idea of making something deadly very pretty. there’s also the dialogue w. craft and taking a “traditional” thing like a dolly and flipping its usage - not only into a more heady “art” space but also in color …

“I am interested in the concept of distance – transitory or spatial, microscopic or global. I am concerned with my personal history and the distances [both literal and figurative] we travel to create the fabric of our lives.” —Lisa Solomon (@LisaSolomon)

Mixed media artist, author, educator, and occasional curator Lisa Solomon is most known for her work deconstructing and questioning the meaning of identity. As a “hapa” (half Caucasian and half Japanese), she is invested in spaces, ideas, and materials that are considered “in-between”: between her European and Japanese ancestry and between art and craft. Lisa explores mediums associated with domestic crafts, which she alters to repurpose their traditional meaning, use, and intent. In doing this, she collapses the space between the contemporary painting and the interior, more domestic world of craft. 

Her ombre colored installation of 1200 dyed french knots in Meta’s Fremont office mirrors her investigation into cultural hybridity, as well as her love of color!

📍Meta’s Fremont office

thinking a lot about basics. drawing. lines. negative space. i’m gonna teach intro drawing again in the fall after several semesters doing other things. 

everything i do is rooted in drawing. drawing clears my head. drawing is immediate. i can be less precious with drawing. i can work the problem. it helps me see. it helps me understand things. 

also it’s portable and can be fast. i don’t have time for full blown studio work at the moment. but i can draw. i can always draw something right in front of me.

social_posts.post_text:
hard to believe it’s already been 2 weeks since my show - cellular memory - opened @slomuseumofart ! 

here’s a quick survey of it - i’m calling it a mini retrospective as it spans many years and several bodies of work and includes a new #giantfrenchknots piece. in ombre indigo the pattern mimics #amime- a japanese fishing net pattern that is used on many decorative objects/fabric and is supposed to bring luck. 

thanks to @emma.lucille_ @leannstandish and all the amazing folks at the museum. to @waltermacielgallery for coming to the opening, my parents @richoak1 for helping w. all the gluing of hardware, @photobickett for cutting rope, @stephenheraldo for fantastic photos, @magnolia.stork for the intro and for the super fun catch up, and @leahmartharosenberg for the beautiful mural on the outside of the building ! 

#lisasolomon #installationart #textileart #fiberart #bayareaartist

Senju Kannon by Lisa Solomon @lisasolomon @a_field_guide_to_color is one of the more than 20 artworks in our upcoming festival, Under the Same Sun, which spotlights Asian American and BIPOC artists and their multimedia artworks, installations, activations and performances throughout Chinatown. 

Senju Kannon is a series of chromatic [red, orange, yellow, green, blue, purple, gray, pink] prints – depicting 1000 Buddha hands (Senju Kannon 1000 armed Buddha). Placed in concentric circles, each hand represents a mudra of blessing/protection and teaching recalling the sacred form of the mandala. 

《千手觀音——Senju Kannon》是一系列彩色 (包含了紅、橙、黃、綠、藍、紫、灰、粉等) 印花所描繪出的一千隻佛手（源自千手觀音或千手佛的概念）。將其放置在同心圓中，每隻手都代表了祝福/庇佑以及開示的結印，讓人聯想起曼荼羅的神聖形式。

What items can you spot in this artwork by Lisa Solomon @lisasolomon @a_field_guide_to_color and Christine Buckton Tillman @christinebucktontillman ?💙

About the Artwork: Chroma @chromainstallation_studio is the result of a long distance collaboration between Lisa Solomon and Christine Buckton Tillman that explores the power of color via objects from everyday life. Chroma is a large-scale crowd-sourced installation made of objects gathered from the community, constructed of various forms of "junk" – arbitrary and otherwise disposable items – that read as one color. The pulling together and reconfiguration of broken objects into a vivid, bright and cheerful composition underscores the potency of transformation, and reframes our perspective around the possibility of repair and new beginnings.  
麗莎·索羅門與克里斯汀·巴克頓·蒂爾曼 (Lisa Solomon x Christine Buckman Tillman) 的合作裝置《色度——Chroma》
《色度——Chroma》是麗莎·索羅門 (Lisa Solomon) 與克里斯汀·巴克頓·蒂爾曼 (Christine Buckton Tillman) 兩位藝術家「長距離合作」的創作成果，通過日常生活中的物體來探索色彩的力量。《色度——Chroma》是一件大型眾籌式裝置作品，由社區所收集來的物品所組成，以各種形式的「垃圾」（任意的廢棄物或一次性使用之物）、讀取為「一種顏色」的構成。將破碎的物體組合一塊兒、並重新聚合出一副生動、明亮而又令人觀感愉悅的構圖，且為觀眾們再度構建新穎視角，圍繞在修復與全新開始的可能性中強調轉變的力量。

This artwork is one of the works in Edge’s current exhibition: Within Others. Learn more about our current exhibition, upcoming programs, and more at Edgeonthesquare.com 🔗 in bio!

I see myself as an optimistic realist. Meaning I don’t expect life to be easy or fun all [or even most] of the time. As we are nearing the end of the year and all the reflection and “turning over new leaves” rhetoric ramps up [even if we attempt to avoid it] I have to admit that the last few years feels like a tipping point. I was just texting with a friend who was asking if this was simply a reflection of where we are in life -  parents are getting ill or passing, so are friends [and in our household sum total of pets we’ve lost is in the double digits]. And YES, I do think this is part of it. But also, the ripple effects of COVID/lockdowns, the sheer amount of death, destruction and FEAR is so very intense. How can you not react to babies being killed or denied food, and shelter? How can you not watch war and think there is anything good about it? [even if you believe people are fighting for good causes]. How can you not wonder about the state of democracy? I have been quiet here - and contemplating the phrase silence = complicity - and also thinking about self preservation. It is hard to paint rainbows and buy presents while staring my comfort and privilege in the face. With war, and famine and climate events occurring on the daily, it seems ridiculous to talk about this time of year and dare to complain about my own problems [like my desire to not have to grade]. Simultaneously I want to acknowledge that to that my core I believe that art and beauty and kindess matter. Maybe more so now than ever. all of this is to say. I SEE you. I appreciate you. And I think whatever you are or maybe are NOT doing should be what is right for you. I am practicing the idea of GRACE. Please text/call your loved ones, hug your family and friends, pet the fur babies. Enjoy a moment of sun on your face. If nothing else I believe that humanity is imperative. Perhaps only then can we actually remember what it is to be human and act humanely.
